---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="RTK — Real-Time Kinematic">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/positioning">Positioning</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>RTK</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Positioning · Article 3 of 5</span>
        <h1>RTK — Real-Time Kinematic</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          RTK delivers centimetre-level positioning by measuring the carrier phase of GNSS signals
          rather than just the code. The challenge is that carrier phase has an unknown number of
          whole cycles — the integer ambiguity — which must be resolved correctly before centimetre
          accuracy is possible. Resolving this ambiguity is the central problem of RTK.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>14 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#why-carrier-phase">Why carrier phase?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#double-difference">Double-differencing</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ambiguity">The integer ambiguity problem</a></li>
          <li><a href="#float-fixed">Float vs fixed solution</a></li>
          <li><a href="#resolution">Ambiguity resolution — LAMBDA</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ttff">Time to first fix</a></li>
          <li><a href="#network-rtk">Network RTK</a></li>
          <li><a href="#limitations">Limitations and failure modes</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="why-carrier-phase">Why carrier phase?</h2>
      <p>
        Code pseudorange measurements have noise of ~0.3 m and systematic errors of several metres.
        The carrier wave — the underlying sine wave onto which the code is modulated — can be
        measured with far greater precision. The GPS L1 carrier has a wavelength of 19.03 cm,
        and a receiver can measure its phase to about 1% of a cycle — roughly <strong>2 mm</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The carrier phase observation from receiver r to satellite i is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">Φ_r^i = (1/λ)·ρ_r^i + N_r^i − f·δt_r + f·δt^i − (1/λ)·I_r^i + (1/λ)·T_r^i + ε</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Φ = carrier phase (cycles), λ = wavelength (m), ρ = geometric range (m),
          N = integer ambiguity (whole cycles — unknown), δt_r = receiver clock offset (s),
          δt^i = satellite clock offset (s), I = ionospheric delay (m), T = tropospheric delay (m),
          ε = measurement noise (~0.002 m).
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The problem is the <strong>integer ambiguity N</strong>. When the receiver first locks
        onto a satellite, it can measure the fractional phase (less than one cycle) very precisely,
        but it has no way to count how many complete wavelengths lie between satellite and receiver.
        N could be 100,000 or 100,001 — both are geometrically consistent with the measurement.
      </p>

      <!-- Phase ambiguity illustration -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">The integer ambiguity — receiver sees fractional phase, not the whole count</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 160" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Satellite -->
          <circle cx="60" cy="40" r="10" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="60" y="26" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)">Satellite</text>
          <!-- Receiver -->
          <rect x="580" y="28" width="50" height="28" rx="4" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="605" y="46" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--sans)">Rx</text>
          <!-- Wave -->
          <path d="M70,42 Q100,18 130,42 Q160,66 190,42 Q220,18 250,42 Q280,66 310,42 Q340,18 370,42 Q400,66 430,42 Q460,18 490,42 Q520,66 550,42 Q565,30 575,34"
            fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.7"/>
          <!-- N cycles brace -->
          <line x1="70" y1="90" x2="550" y2="90" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <line x1="70" y1="84" x2="70" y2="96" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <line x1="550" y1="84" x2="550" y2="96" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <text x="310" y="108" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--text2)" font-family="var(--mono)">N whole cycles (unknown integer)</text>
          <!-- Fractional part brace -->
          <line x1="550" y1="118" x2="580" y2="118" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <line x1="550" y1="112" x2="550" y2="124" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <line x1="580" y1="112" x2="580" y2="124" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <text x="565" y="140" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--mono)">φ (measured)</text>
          <text x="310" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Total range = (N + φ) × λ — must solve for N</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="double-difference">Double-differencing</h2>
      <p>
        The raw carrier phase observation contains multiple nuisance terms — receiver clock error,
        satellite clock error, ionospheric delay, tropospheric delay. RTK removes these by forming
        <strong>double differences</strong> between measurements.
      </p>

      <h3>Step 1 — Single difference (between receivers)</h3>
      <p>
        Subtract the reference station's phase observation from the rover's for the same satellite.
        This cancels the satellite clock error (identical for both receivers at the same epoch):
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ΔΦ^i = Φ_rover^i − Φ_ref^i = (1/λ)·Δρ^i + ΔN^i − f·Δδt_r − (1/λ)·ΔI^i + (1/λ)·ΔT^i</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Δ denotes between-receiver difference. Satellite clock δt^i cancels exactly.
          Ionospheric and tropospheric delays become small residuals (proportional to baseline length).
          ΔN^i = N_rover^i − N_ref^i — still an integer, still unknown.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Step 2 — Double difference (between receivers and satellites)</h3>
      <p>
        Now subtract the single-difference for a reference satellite j from the single-difference
        for satellite i. This cancels the receiver clock error:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">∇ΔΦ^ij = ΔΦ^i − ΔΦ^j = (1/λ)·∇Δρ^ij + ∇ΔN^ij − (1/λ)·∇ΔI^ij + (1/λ)·∇ΔT^ij + ε</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          ∇Δ denotes double difference. Receiver clock error Δδt_r cancels exactly.
          ∇ΔN^ij = (N_rover^i − N_ref^i) − (N_rover^j − N_ref^j) — an integer combination.
          With n satellites, there are n−1 independent double differences.
          Residual ionosphere and troposphere are small for short baselines (&lt;20 km).
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="differencing-visual">
        <div class="diff-row">
          <div class="diff-label">Raw phase</div>
          <div class="diff-terms">
            <span class="term-keep">range</span>
            <span class="term-keep">N (unknown)</span>
            <span class="term-cancel">rx clock</span>
            <span class="term-cancel">sv clock</span>
            <span class="term-keep">iono</span>
            <span class="term-keep">tropo</span>
            <span class="term-keep">noise</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="diff-row">
          <div class="diff-label">Single diff</div>
          <div class="diff-terms">
            <span class="term-keep">Δrange</span>
            <span class="term-keep">ΔN</span>
            <span class="term-keep">rx clock</span>
            <span class="term-gone">sv clock ✓</span>
            <span class="term-small">ΔI (small)</span>
            <span class="term-small">ΔT (small)</span>
            <span class="term-keep">noise</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="diff-row">
          <div class="diff-label">Double diff</div>
          <div class="diff-terms">
            <span class="term-keep">∇Δrange</span>
            <span class="term-keep">∇ΔN (integer!)</span>
            <span class="term-gone">rx clock ✓</span>
            <span class="term-gone">sv clock ✓</span>
            <span class="term-small">∇ΔI (tiny)</span>
            <span class="term-small">∇ΔT (tiny)</span>
            <span class="term-keep">noise</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="ambiguity">The integer ambiguity problem</h2>
      <p>
        After double-differencing, the unknowns are the <strong>baseline components</strong>
        (Δx, Δy, Δz — the vector from reference to rover) and the <strong>integer ambiguities</strong>
        ∇ΔN^ij for each satellite pair. The double-differenced observation equation is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">∇ΔΦ^ij = (1/λ)·∇Δρ^ij(Δx,Δy,Δz) + ∇ΔN^ij + ε</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The geometric term ∇Δρ^ij depends on the baseline and the known satellite positions.
          With n satellites, there are n−1 double-difference equations and n−1 integer unknowns
          plus 3 baseline components = (n+2) unknowns total. With enough epochs and satellites,
          the system is overdetermined.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The difficulty is that N must be an <em>integer</em> — not just any real number. Finding
        the correct integers from real-valued least squares estimates is the core computational
        challenge of RTK, known as <strong>integer least squares</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="float-fixed">Float vs fixed solution</h2>
      <p>
        RTK processing proceeds through distinct stages, each with different accuracy:
      </p>

      <div class="solution-stages">
        <div class="stage stage-code">
          <div class="stage-name">Code solution</div>
          <div class="stage-acc">~0.3 – 1.0 m</div>
          <div class="stage-desc">
            Differential code (pseudorange) solution. Fast — available immediately.
            Used as starting point for float solution initialisation.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="stage stage-float">
          <div class="stage-name">Float solution</div>
          <div class="stage-acc">~0.05 – 0.3 m</div>
          <div class="stage-desc">
            Carrier phase included but ambiguities treated as real numbers (not constrained to integers).
            Kalman filter accumulates measurements. Accuracy improves over time as filter converges.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="stage stage-fixed">
          <div class="stage-name">Fixed solution</div>
          <div class="stage-acc">~0.01 – 0.03 m</div>
          <div class="stage-desc">
            Integer ambiguities resolved and fixed to correct integers. Position computed from
            carrier phase with known integers — centimetre accuracy. The goal state.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Wrong fix is worse than float:</strong> If ambiguities are fixed to the wrong
          integers — a <em>wrong fix</em> — the position error is a multiple of the wavelength
          (~19 cm on L1) and can be metres. A float solution with 0.2 m accuracy is safer than
          a wrong fix with 0.5 m error. Quality RTK engines implement validation tests (ratio test,
          ADOP, success rate) to ensure fixes are accepted only when they are very likely correct.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="resolution">Ambiguity resolution — LAMBDA</h2>
      <p>
        The standard algorithm for integer ambiguity resolution is <strong>LAMBDA</strong>
        (Least-squares AMBiguity Decorrelation Adjustment), developed by Peter Teunissen at
        Delft University of Technology in 1993. It remains the industry standard.
      </p>
      <p>
        LAMBDA operates in three steps:
      </p>

      <ol class="steps">
        <li>
          <strong>Float solution:</strong> Estimate ambiguities as real numbers â with covariance
          matrix Q_â using least squares or Kalman filter. The ambiguities are highly correlated —
          directly searching the integer space would be computationally prohibitive.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Decorrelation (Z-transformation):</strong> Apply an integer transformation
          Z to decorrelate the ambiguities: ẑ = Z·â. The transformed ambiguities have much
          smaller, more nearly equal variances, reducing the search space from an elongated
          ellipsoid to a near-sphere. This is the key innovation of LAMBDA.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Integer search:</strong> Search for the integer vector ž that minimises the
          weighted sum of squares (J = (ž − ẑ)ᵀ Q_ẑ⁻¹ (ž − ẑ)) within an ellipsoidal
          search region. Return the best candidate ž₁ and second-best ž₂.
          Transform back: N̂ = Z⁻ᵀ·ž₁.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ratio = J(ž₂) / J(ž₁)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The <strong>ratio test</strong> validates the fix. If the second-best solution is much
          worse than the best (ratio &gt; threshold, typically 2.0–3.0), the fix is accepted.
          A low ratio means two competing integer solutions are close — the fix is uncertain.
          Never accept a fix with ratio &lt; 1.5 for precision applications.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="ttff">Time to first fix</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>TTFF</strong> (Time to First Fix) is how long RTK takes to resolve the integer
        ambiguities and deliver a fixed solution after initialisation. It depends on several factors:
      </p>

      <div class="ttff-grid">
        <div class="ttff-card">
          <div class="ttff-factor">Baseline length</div>
          <div class="ttff-detail">Short baselines (&lt;5 km) have negligible differential ionosphere — ambiguities resolve in seconds. Long baselines need ionospheric modelling or dual-frequency to decorrelate.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ttff-card">
          <div class="ttff-factor">Number of frequencies</div>
          <div class="ttff-detail">Dual and triple frequency receivers form widelane (86.2 cm wavelength for L1/L2) and narrowlane combinations that greatly accelerate ambiguity resolution. Single-frequency RTK can take 1–5 minutes.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ttff-card">
          <div class="ttff-factor">Number of satellites</div>
          <div class="ttff-detail">More satellites = more independent observations = faster convergence. Multi-constellation (GPS+Galileo+BeiDou) can reduce TTFF from minutes to seconds.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ttff-card">
          <div class="ttff-factor">Ionospheric activity</div>
          <div class="ttff-detail">High Kp or scintillation introduces rapidly changing biases that prevent stable ambiguity resolution. Single-frequency RTK may fail entirely during G3+ geomagnetic storms.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ttff-comparison">
        <div class="ttff-title">Typical TTFF by configuration</div>
        <div class="ttff-row">
          <div class="ttff-config">Single-freq, GPS only, 10 km baseline</div>
          <div class="ttff-time bad">2 – 10 min</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ttff-row">
          <div class="ttff-config">Dual-freq, GPS only, 10 km baseline</div>
          <div class="ttff-time warn">30 – 120 s</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ttff-row">
          <div class="ttff-config">Dual-freq, GPS+Galileo, 10 km baseline</div>
          <div class="ttff-time ok">10 – 30 s</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ttff-row">
          <div class="ttff-config">Triple-freq, GPS+Galileo+BeiDou, &lt;5 km</div>
          <div class="ttff-time good">3 – 10 s</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="network-rtk">Network RTK</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional RTK requires a single base station within ~20 km of the rover. Network RTK
        (also called VRS — Virtual Reference Station) extends this to regional scale using a
        network of reference stations.
      </p>
      <p>
        The network processes observations from all reference stations simultaneously to model
        spatially correlated errors — ionosphere, troposphere, orbit and clock — across the
        network. When a rover connects (typically via NTRIP), the network generates a
        <strong>Virtual Reference Station</strong> with synthetic observations as if a base
        station were located just a few kilometres from the rover. The rover then runs standard
        RTK against this virtual base.
      </p>

      <div class="network-benefits">
        <div class="net-benefit">
          <div class="net-icon">📍</div>
          <div class="net-title">Single receiver operation</div>
          <div class="net-desc">No need to own or maintain a base station. Connect to an NTRIP caster via cellular data.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="net-benefit">
          <div class="net-icon">🗺️</div>
          <div class="net-title">Consistent accuracy continent-wide</div>
          <div class="net-desc">Ionospheric and tropospheric modelling keeps accuracy consistent regardless of distance from any individual station.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="net-benefit">
          <div class="net-icon">⚡</div>
          <div class="net-title">Faster TTFF</div>
          <div class="net-desc">Better error modelling means ambiguities resolve faster — typically &lt;10 s with good multi-constellation coverage.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🌐</div>
        <div>
          <strong>CORS networks:</strong> Continuously Operating Reference Station (CORS) networks
          provide network RTK corrections. Examples include NOAA CORS (USA), OS Net (UK),
          SAPOS (Germany) and AUSPOS (Australia). Most require a subscription fee of
          $50–$300/month. Commercial networks (Trimble RTX, Leica SmartNet, TopNET) offer
          similar services with guaranteed SLAs.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="limitations">Limitations and failure modes</h2>

      <div class="limitation-list">
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Cycle slips</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            When a satellite signal is briefly lost (tree canopy, bridge, building), the receiver
            loses track of the carrier phase — a <strong>cycle slip</strong> occurs. The integer
            ambiguity counter resets. The receiver must re-initialise ambiguities for that satellite,
            degrading to float until new ambiguities are resolved. Frequent cycle slips prevent
            fixed solution in difficult environments.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Multipath</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            Carrier phase multipath (max ~9.5 cm, typically ~1–2 cm) introduces slowly varying
            biases that cannot be differenced away. In severe multipath environments (urban canyons,
            reflective surfaces), multipath becomes the dominant RTK error source even with a
            perfect fixed solution.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Baseline length limit</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            Single-base RTK accuracy degrades beyond 20–30 km due to differential ionosphere.
            For L1-only: practical limit ~10 km. For L1+L2 dual-frequency: ~30–50 km.
            Network RTK removes this constraint by modelling the ionosphere spatially.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Ionospheric scintillation</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            Rapid signal amplitude and phase fluctuations (S4 index &gt; 0.3, σφ &gt; 0.1 rad)
            cause frequent cycle slips and prevent ambiguity resolution. Particularly severe
            at equatorial latitudes after local sunset. See the
            <a href="/dashboards/environment">GNSS Environment Watch</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Data link latency</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            RTK requires real-time corrections from the base station or network.
            Correction latency &gt;1–2 s degrades performance due to rapid satellite motion.
            Cellular NTRIP with &lt;500 ms latency is generally adequate. Satellite uplink
            or radio modem systems must be carefully designed for low latency.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">〰️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Carrier phase precision</div>
          <div class="summary-body">The 19 cm GPS L1 carrier can be measured to ~2 mm — 100× better than code. This is the source of RTK accuracy.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">➖</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Double-differencing</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Differencing between receivers removes satellite clock error. Differencing between satellites removes receiver clock error. Residuals are small differential iono, tropo and noise.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔢</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Integer ambiguity</div>
          <div class="summary-body">The unknown whole-cycle count N must be resolved to a correct integer before centimetre accuracy is achievable. LAMBDA is the standard algorithm. A wrong fix is worse than float.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Network RTK</div>
          <div class="summary-body">VRS/network RTK extends coverage to regional scale without owning a base station. Better error modelling improves TTFF and extends baseline range to 100+ km.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/positioning/dgnss-and-sbas" class="nav-prev">← DGNSS and SBAS</a>
        <a href="/learn/positioning/ppp" class="nav-next">PPP →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. (1993). Least-squares estimation of the integer GPS ambiguities. <em>Invited lecture, Section IV Theory and Methodology, IAG General Meeting</em>, Beijing, China.</li>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. & Montenbruck, O. (eds.) (2017). <em>Springer Handbook of Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Springer. Chapter 23.</li>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapter 9.</li>
          <li>Verhagen, S. & Teunissen, P. J. G. (2013). The ratio test for future GNSS ambiguity resolution. <em>GPS Solutions</em>, 17, 535–548.</li>
          <li>RTCM 10403.3 Standard for Differential GNSS Services. <a href="https://www.rtcm.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtcm.org →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

